The paper proposes a multiple imputation model based on deep denoising autoencoders, which is a machine learning technique falling under the sub-category of "Machine Learning" (cs.LG). The proposed model is capable of handling different data types, missingness patterns, missingness proportions and distributions, which suggests the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of "Artificial Intelligence" (cs.AI) and "Databases" (cs.DB). The paper also mentions evaluation on real-life datasets, which suggests it may belong to the sub-categories of "Neural and Evolutionary Computing" (cs.NE) and "Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition" (cs.CV).
